# 9. Database Scaling: Database scaling is critical when traffic increases significantly.
Two main types: 
Vertical Scaling: 
Increase hardware capacity of the server.
Advantages: Easy to implement, No architectural change
Limitations: Hardware limits exist, Expensive, Single machine dependency

Horizontal Scaling: Add more database nodes. Instead of one database server, use multiple servers.
Benefits: Unlimited scaling potential, Better fault tolerance, Improved performance

---
# Database Sharding
Horizontal scaling is implemented using sharding.
Sharding divides data across multiple databases.
Two types:
# Row-Based Sharding: Rows distributed across different databases.
Example: DB1 → rows 1–100, DB2 → rows 101–200
Problem: Joins across shards become difficult.

# Column-Based Sharding (Vertical Sharding): Split table columns into multiple tables.
Used when different services need different sets of data.

# Challenges in Sharding
Uneven data distribution.

